{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01Mir2YbA1b56sxyaC34udmv","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear plan for the changes:\n\n1. Add `@rng-utopia/price-feeds` as a dependency in `apps/platform/package.json`\n2. Rewrite `CloseCallContext.tsx`:\n   - Remove all mock-simulation imports\n   - Add `usePriceSubscription(\"BTC\")` from price-feeds \n   - Add backend API fetch for `/closecall/current-round` (poll every 2s)\n   - Add backend API fetch for `/closecall/history` for recent rounds\n   - Keep `placeBet()` as a stub (wallet tx wired in next iteration)\n\n\n3. Wrap the CloseCallProvider with PriceFeedProvider and remove the candle-replay price interpolation in favor of real Pyth prices\n4. For candles, I need to map the backend's round data (which has openPrice, closePrice, and timestamps) into the Candle format with OHLC values, pulling from either the settled rounds history or the live price feed itself I need to keep `placeBet()` as a stub for now since the wallet integration comes later. For the candles, I'll accumulate OHLC data from the live price feed and combine it with historical rounds from the backend to build out the chart data.\n\nDefining the backend types... Continuing the conversion function... Finishing up the round object with close price and settlement transaction details. Now I'm thinking through the implementation strategy — I need to add the PriceFeedProvider to the component tree within CloseCallProvider, then build local 1-minute candles by aggregating OHLC data from live Pyth price updates. The core requirements are swapping out the mock imports for real backend API calls, polling rounds every 2 seconds, integrating the price subscription hook, keeping placeBet as a stub for now, and making sure the linter passes and the page renders. I need to set up the real-time price feed properly — using `usePriceSubscription` to get the current price, building candles locally from incoming ticks on each minute boundary, and calculating progress based on elapsed time within the current minute. The existing interpolation logic won't be needed since I'm working with actual live prices rather than synthetic data. Now I'm setting up the context providers and fetching the necessary backend data to wire everything together. Setting up the imports and constants for the price feed integration...\n\nDefining the backend response types and converting them to the frontend Round format... Building the round object... Writing the fetch functions...\n\nNow I'm thinking about how to build candles from live price data. I'll create a hook that accumulates price ticks into candle objects, tracking the open, high, low, and close prices for each time period. Updating the current candle with the latest price movement, then returning the full candle history including the one still forming. Wait, refs don't trigger re-renders—I need to rethink this approach. Actually, I'm overcomplicating it. The price updates frequently from Pyth and I can derive candleProgress from the clock, so I should just maintain an empty candles array and build it up from price ticks using a ref to track state.\n\nThe context already has a 100ms polling interval from the mock candle interpolation, so I can repurpose that to update candleProgress based on the current time relative to minute boundaries and use the real Pyth price directly without interpolation. For the candles themselves, I'll accumulate price ticks in a ref and flush them to state periodically or when crossing minute boundaries.\n\nLet me check how the consuming components actually use `recentCandles` to make sure this approach fits their needs.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":607,"cache_read_input_tokens":75904,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":607},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"st